a352e.textContent:
CELL-SPECIFIC  REGULATORS OF
DEATH DURING DEVELOPMENT

comments.content: Released CED-4 proteins translocate to perinuclear membranes and undergo oligomerization, which brings two CED-3 proenzymes to close proximity.
In cells that are doomed to die, the death initiator EGL-1 binds to CED-9, causes a major CED-9 conformational change, and triggers the disassociation of CED-4 from CED-9.
High EGL-1 activity inhibits CED-9 activity, resulting in the activation of CED-4 and CED-3 and the commitment of a cell to the cell death fate (Horvitz, 2003)
